04783nam a2200625Ia 9780292736443DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20141989txu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1301272056  a97802927364437 a10.7560/7304582doi  a(DE-B1597)588062  a(OCoLC)1286808704  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aBIO0000002bisacsh04a338.0921 aFoster, Mark S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHenry J. Kaiser :bBuilder in the Modern American West /cMark S. Foster. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2014] 4c©1989  a1 online resource (406 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Studies Series00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Roots -- t2. Launching a Career -- t3. Taming the Wilderness—Roads -- t4. Taming the Wilderness—Dams -- t5. Patriot in Pinstripes—Shipbuilding -- t6. Man of Steel -- t7. Creating an Image -- t8. Planning for a Postwar World -- t9. Debacle in Detroit -- t10. Venturing Abroad -- t11. Cargo Planes and Government Investigations -- t12. Light Metals—Heavy Profits -- t13. Kaiser and the Doctors -- t14. Boss -- t15. Global Development and a Pacific Paradise -- t16. The Sunset Years -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliographic Note -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1940s Henry J. Kaiser was a household name, as familiar then as Warren Buffett and Donald Trump are now. Like a Horatio Alger hero, Kaiser rose from lower-middle-class origins to become an enormously wealthy entrepreneur, building roads, bridges, dams, and housing. He established giant businesses in cement, aluminum, chemicals, steel, health care, and tourism. During World War II, his companies built cargo planes and Liberty ships. After the war, he manufactured the Kaiser-Frazer automobile. Along the way, he also became a major force in the development of the western United States, including Hawaii. Henry J. Kaiser: Builder in the Modern American West is the first biography of this remarkable man. Drawing on a wealth of archival material never before utilized, Mark Foster paints an evenhanded portrait of a man of driving ambition and integrity, perhaps the ultimate "can-do" capitalist. He covers Kaiser's entire life (1882–1967), emphasizing many business ventures. He demonstrates that Kaiser was the prototypical "frontier" entrepreneur who often used government and union support to tame the "wilderness." Though today the Kaiser industries are no longer under family management, the Kaiser legacy remains great. Kaiser played a major role in building the Hoover, Bonneville, Grand Coulee, and Shasta dams. The Kaiser-Permanente Medical Care Program still provides comprehensive health care for millions of subscribers. Kaiser-planned communities remain in Los Angeles; San Francisco; Portland, Oregon; and Boulder City, Nevada. Kaiser Engineers was actively engaged in hundreds of huge construction jobs across the nation and around the world. U.S. and business historians, scholars of the modern West, and general readers will all find much to absorb them in this well-written biography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aKaiser, Henry J. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aGoetzmann, William H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311074535140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73045840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292736443423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292736443/original  a978-3-11-074535-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000b